Johannesburg - The City of Ekurhuleni has warned that rumours that water restrictions have been lifted are untrue. In fact, to the contrary, residents and businesses in the city have not yet achieved a savings of 15% imposed by national government it sits on 8 percent much lower than Joburg which sits on 10.5 percent and Tshwane 19.5 percent. City spokesperson Themba Gadebe said water savings are monitored on a weekly basis and since the implementation of the restrictions, it has yet to reach this target. At a meeting on December 7 with the Department of Water and Sanitation, Rand Water and municipalities, these figures were disclosed, he said.&nbsp; Ekurhuleni has implemented water rationing from 9pm 5am in the evenings in all areas according to a roster, available on the city s website. Various engagements had been held with the business sector in Ekurhuleni, he said, who were responding well to the call of saving water. An appeal goes out to all residents to heed the call and pledge with the city to save water. In the first week of December, the Vaal Dam s level was 37% which was due to augmentation from Katse, as well as head waters from Sterkfontein, which will be stopped on 22 December, he said. The restrictions will only be reviewed in May next year. Restrictions that apply: &middot; Low pressure to curb water use across the region. &middot; Use of hosepipe and sprinkler system is prohibited. &middot; No filling of swimming pool with municipal water. &middot; No watering from 6am to 6pm. Thereafter only with a watering can/bucket. &middot; 25kl monthly consumption limit on households. If this is exceeded, a 10% fine is imposed. Should the above not be adhered to, including illegal water connections, for example using fire hydrants, a fine of R6 753.64 will be imposed on households per incident. For businesses, this fine is R13 762.24. Any incidents can be reported to the City via email. Please include a photograph, stipulate the address (GPS coordinates if available), time and details and email to [email&#160;protected] By standing together we can ensure that we save this life giving resource, because if we don t there will be no water, Ekurhuleni s Spokesperson Themba Gadebe cautioned. Residents are requested to ensure that they to fix all water leaks on their properties and report those outside of properties to the following platforms. City s call centre via: &middot; 0860 543 000 &middot; SMS details to 30788 &middot; Email [email&#160;protected] &middot; Twitter @EMM_Call_Centre @annacox [email&#160;protected] The Star